[3] Asymptomatic transmission
Date: Mon 10 Feb 2020
From: Dr. Camilla Rothe <rothe@lrz.uni-muenchen.de> [edited]


2019-nCoV asymptomatic transmission in Germany - interview with Chinese index patient
--------------------------------------
During the past days, the press was informed about alleged fraud in association with our letter published in the New England Journal of Medicine on 30 Jan 2020 (Rothe C et al., "Transmission of 2019-nCoV Infection from an Asymptomatic Contact in Germany"). At the center of criticism was the question, if the patient was rightly termed "asymptomatic" or whether she had rather shown some possible prodromal symptoms.

Given the current situation with a rapidly spreading epidemic and an overall lack of solid data, we felt the need to report our observations to the medical world as fast as possible. Our conclusions were therefore chiefly based upon observations of our own patients, who had spent 3 days of intense business meetings and workshops with the Chinese index patient without noticing any clinical signs of a possible respiratory infection. Until the time the letter was published, however, we did not have the chance to talk to the index patient ourselves.

In the meantime, we were granted the opportunity to talk to the index-patient in China on the phone and ask her about possible symptoms she might have had during her visit in Germany. We have published the results of our enquiry as an addendum in NEJM so that the medical world will get an opportunity to judge by themselves if the patient showed any relevant symptoms or not.

According to the personal opinion of the authors, the message of our initial letter still stands.

Link to the new appendix: https://www.nejm.org/doi/suppl/10.1056/NEJMc2001468/suppl_file/nejmc2001468_appendix.pdf

--
Dr. Camilla Rothe
<rothe@lrz.uni-muenchen.de>
LMU Hospital Munich, Div. of Infectious Diseases and Tropical Medicine

[ProMED-mail would like to thank Dr. Rothe for her and her colleagues' contributions.

The supplementary appendix contains the actual interview with the patient.

"Supplementary Material
To clarify whether the index patient has been correctly described as asymptomatic, a group of the authors spoke with her by telephone on 5 Feb 2020. What follows is her description of the way her symptoms developed.

Sun 19 Jan 2020
1:35 a.m. local time - Take-off from Shanghai.
6:30 a.m. local time - Arrival in Munich on a direct flight.
She noticed that a person was coughing in the rows behind her own row.

Mon 20 Jan 2020
1st meeting day, Webex conference in the morning, various other business meetings in the afternoon. No symptoms whatsoever during the workday. At midnight she woke up, felt "a little bit warm, but not in a febrile way," took one pill of a Chinese over-the-counter drug called 999 (solution in water), which, according to her, contained acetaminophen. She took it as a "preventive measure to be fit for the following day," when various intense business meetings and workshops were scheduled. This was the only time during her stay in Germany that she reported taking any kind of medication.

Tue 21 Jan 2020
Felt tired after 3:00 p.m. She ascribed this to the time difference, as this was her bedtime at home in China (10:00 p.m.). She noticed some minor pain "in some muscles and the bones of her chest" when she touched certain trigger points. She did not feel "warm" again, nor did she have any other symptoms.

Wed 22 Jan 2020
All day meetings until 6:00 p.m. She mentioned that she had felt slightly cold in the morning when wearing light business attire. This ended when she used a shawl. Flight out of Munich at 10:20 p.m.

Thu 23 Jan 2020
Arrival at 4:00 p.m. local time in Shanghai. Felt tired upon arrival, but otherwise healthy. On the evening of the same day, she reported feeling sick. ("This is the 1st moment I recognized getting sick.") She recorded the temperature at around midnight (approx. 38 deg C [100.4 deg F]); there were some localized chest pains as well.

Fri 24 Jan 2020
Went to get medicine in the hospital for her sick father and was busy all day. Recorded a temperature of 38.7 deg C [101.7 deg. F] in the evening.

Sat 25 Jan 2020
Went to see a doctor and was hospitalized.

Sun 26 Jan 2020
Developed an infrequent dry cough.

Mon 27 Jan 2020
Transferred to a different hospital.

Tue 28 Jan 2020
Cough turned productive; it lasted for 3 further days and then subsided.

Wed 5 Feb 2020
Interview. She was still hospitalized."

While the definition of asymptomatic vs a mild viral prodrome that was missed by other observers and the affected individual may be debated, what is noteworthy is in the revision of the original report, there is mention of follow-up viral load assays of sputum of the index case in Germany after he had recovered and had no further symptoms?: "Follow-up qRT-PCR assay revealed a high viral load of 108 copies per milliliter in his sputum during the following days, with the last available result on [29 Jan 2020]" The authors conclude: "The detection of 2019-nCoV and a high sputum viral load in a convalescent patient (Patient 1) arouse concern about prolonged shedding of 2019-nCoV after recovery. Yet, the viability of 2019-nCoV detected on qRT-PCR in this patient remains to be proved by means of viral culture."

More questions to be answered. - Mod.MPP]

