[5] False negative NAT tests: comment/query
Date: Mon 10 Feb 2020
From: Richard Gould <jrichard.gould@bell.net> [edited]

This is an interesting posting. I'm curious about how the rate of false negatives could be determined without comparison to a "gold standard"? Does such a "gold standard" exist for novel coronavirus infections in order to accurately determine the rates of false positives and negatives? And in the middle of influenza season (a virus with significant morbidity and mortality) when many other respiratory viruses are circulating, wouldn't the determination of false negative rates be challenging if this is based primarily on clinical symptoms?

--
J Richard Gould MD MHSc FRCPC
<jrichard.gould@bell.net>
York Region Public Health

[Dr. Gould raises valid points here. This article was posted to raise the issue of multiple anecdotal reports of false negative tests in the early stages of illness in China. Many of these anecdotal reports were in sensationalist reports, print media, and social media. It merits discussion on the need for formal studies addressing the sensitivity and specificity of the NAT tests being used. -Mod.MPP]

